Text.Value: Where is he? Spit it out - Now.
Only what I can smell. And whatever engine burns within you is grinding to an inevitable explosion. Burning and fear - you reek with it.
My dear hunter, isn't it obvious? You must kill yourself - then you'll be free.
Stay very still, my beauty...

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Levels his crossbow at the displacer

Text.Value: Bold of you. Stupid, but bold.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry. Not overly concerned that the player's about to attack (combat ensues after this line)

Text.Value: Bravo.
You're hardly free as it is, trapped here. Maybe you're better off indebted to Raphael.
Not surprised this guy stomped all those Dark Justiciars. It's what orthons do.
Words. A contract penned by that deceitful slug Raphael.
Haggling. A grubby little trait. Fine, there's a gem I keep over by my bed. Kill the justiciar, and it's yours.
Raphael made double-sure of that: I can't forget the damned thing so long as my work's not finished.
Perhaps I can help you escape his trap.
...That's it.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Slight smile as he considers the player, as if he's realised something.
EditorData.NodeContext: A little knowing (double meaning in 'that's it' - the song has ended, but he also thinks he's stumbled upon a revelation in the lyrics.)

Text.Value: Not surprised this guy single-handedly wiped out the Dark Justiciars here. Fucker is stacked.
That perfumed trickster swindled me - trapped me.
Hah! Perhaps this is true of the mundane traps you know. But I am held here by something stronger.

EditorData.stateContext: Orthon has his crossbow aimed from the hip at the player

Text.Value: Bargaining, are you? A Kara-Tur warlord once tried the same - I made him watch as I ate his concubines and young, then fashioned a codpiece from his skull.

EditorData.NodeContext: Menacing - 'You think you can negotiate?' Pronunciation: kah-rah-TOOR

Text.Value: Attack.
Does... does that count as us killing him? That had better count.
Tell him, or don't - it doesn't matter, so long as you grant me the killing blow.
I did as instructed, but the song still rattles about in my head - the contract still stands, somehow. If I break it, I will become Raphael's slave forever.
Such high confidence for someone who reeks so distinctively of fear.

EditorData.stateContext: Orthon no longer singing. Crossbow still in hand, but not pointed at player

Text.Value:
Leave none to hear it, then be set free;
This song is your oath, swear, swear it to me.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The orthon sings to the player.

Text.Value: *This song differs from others you've studied. The final couplet contains a trick: a clause not easily fulfilled.*
*The final lyrics linger in your mind. There is a trick buried within them - a clause that cannot easily be fulfilled.*

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node only if the player passes a passive check or if they are a bard.

Text.Value: Oh no, little rabbit. You don't get to just hop away.
Anyway, enough prattle. The lyrics are clear - all who hear the song must die.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Tilts his head and looks at the player, as if appraising them.

Text.Value: Then they failed her, and you never met a true servant of Shar.
Raphael is no foolish story-devil, his mind is different. Sneaky. Listen...
You are mouthy, little rabbit. This will be -

EditorData.NodeContext:
Scornful, but then breaks off before finishing the line
(Full version would be 'This will be over quickly'' if he'd finished it)

Text.Value: I still hear it. Seems your theory is wrong.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Cocks his head slightly, as if listening to something, then glares at the player.
EditorData.NodeContext: Temper building. Thinks he's been dupped.

Text.Value: I happen to be an expert in such deals - and there is always a loophole.
I deal in blood and bones - not cogs and wrenches. Tell me what I wish to know, or you'll find that out first hand.
Time to die.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Raises his crossbow and points it at the player.

Text.Value: I don't know what you mean.
Go on then. But if you're lying - if you run - there'll be nowhere that's safe for you.
There's nothing stopping you from leaving. I know a way out.
Shar is not my goddess, but I can respect her. I ought to kill you for what you have done to her temple.
Raphael could be anywhere. But let me go, and I'll free you from his grasp.
You blaspheme this holy place. I must strike you down.
So he's the one who slaughtered the justiciars - we can kill him now?
While two devils fight over a bone - well, we should just run away and let them sort it among themselves.
Your words thrum with violence. Peace - let us speak.
What, they're no longer worth avenging? You're a fickle creature, little Sharran.
You're not finished yet - the displacer can hear you, can't she? Kill her.
Displacer hearing is notoriously sharp. You must kill her too.
A servant of Zariel, if I'm not mistaken. I'd know the stench of her infernal machinery anywhere.
He wants you dead.
Quite bloodthirsty, as lyrics go. Have you considered some instrumental accompaniment?
Your contract is a song?
Run.

EditorData.stateContext: Orthon singing. Crossbow still in hand, but not pointed at player

Text.Value: Wait - there's one last Dark Justiciar. I met him.
Well? Tell him. We owe the devil nothing.
Maybe that's true, maybe not - but I don't have to let you live in order to find out.
That was awful - perhaps you should stick to killing.
The devil has been stalking my companions - what dealings do you have with him?

EditorData.stateContext: Orthon has sword in hand. Crossbow discarded.

Text.Value: Nicely played, Raphael. Bastard.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The orthon looks upward, as if addressing Raphael up on the surface.

Text.Value: Damn. Now there's something I never thought I'd see. Brutal.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not too heartbroken, kind of bemused

Text.Value: I'll burrow my fist into your chest if you don't stop mouthing off.
I may stink of the surface, but it's not where I hail from.
*Well, that explains where all the dark justiciars went.*
So he's the one who killed all the Dark Justiciars. Alone. Might not want to get on his bad side.
An acceptable conclusion. But it is a shame I won't know the pleasure of executing a wardevil.
But go on - spill some blood prove me wrong. If there truly is a justiciar, the song will end and you will be vindicated.
I'm not your errand boy, or your butcher.
I'm not your errand girl, or your butcher.
I'm not your errand-runner, or your butcher.
You give them too much credit. And show more spine than they did - at least until I flayed them.
Because if he doesn't die, then Raphael won't tell me a damn thing about my scars.
The merregons? They barely have a thought to share among themselves... but they do have ears.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: <placeholder>

Text.Value: I don't keep company with devils.
Well, allow me to hop to it - I want to talk.
This 'rabbit' has hunted prey larger than you. I suggest you choose your next words wisely.

Spill all the blood sworn to the night.
Silence all prayers; smother each rite.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The orthon sings to the player.

Text.Value: Either I fulfil the contract, die trying... or forfeit my freedom. If I leave this place now, I'll become Raphael's slave.
Shar is not my goddess, but I can respect her. I ought to kill you for what you have done to her temple.
Parchment can burn. Oral agreements aren't worth the tongues they're waggled out upon. A song lingers.
It's Raphael you want, not me.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Yurgir] an orthon aims a crossbow at the player (aimed from the hip) <Greg>
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext:
The player enters a gore-soaked alcove and approaches the displacer.There's various severed heads on display - people and monsters. A pile of eviscerated corpses forms a throne-chaise.
There's suddenly a loud click from above (implied to be the orthon racking/loading its crossbow). The player looks up.
The orthon looms on a gallery/crumpling floor overlooking the alcove. It aims a crossbow at the player. Flanking it are several merregons.

Text.Value: Well. There is always next time.
Asking why doesn't get me paid - hunting and killing does. Raphael mentioned something about an aasimar. Meant nothing to me.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Aasimar reference being a hint towards Nightsong.

Text.Value: All right, leave it to me.
...There's something else, almost hidden by your fear-stink... cherries, musk... and sulphur.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Sniffs the air, then face suddenly overcome by shock and anger on 'sulphur'
EditorData.NodeContext: Sniffing the air at the start, detecting something - then erupting with fury at the end on 'sulphur'.
EditorData.SFXTags: [MO] [NoJira] - Sniffing sfx if not included in VO recording.

Text.Value: Attack.
Stupid rabbit. Running can't save you.
Kill yourselves - back to the hells with you.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: <placeholder>
EditorData.NodeContext: Addressing the merregons. Matter of fact, like he's telling them they can clock off early.

Text.Value: The likes of you is frightened of a contract? I find that hard to swallow.
Balduran's bones, what a performance - you'd put the Five Flagons to shame!
Wait - you know Raphael?
There must be something you missed. Let me search this place for you.
I don't talk to prey, I -

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: <placeholder>
EditorData.NodeContext:
Scornful, but then breaks off before finishing the line
(Full version would be 'I don't talk to prey, I skin them' if he'd finished it)

Text.Value: What do you know about infernal machinery?
You can't help. It's not just walls that keep me here. Not the traps, the dark or the creatures it hides. Something stronger holds me - a contract.
A pact made from song? Quite quaint for a devil, I must say.
Kill yourself, coward. Then you'll return to Avernus. You'll be free.
You desecrated Shar's temple? You slew her children? I ought to kill you.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [merregons] kills each other, [Player] reacts to the gore
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The merregons pair off, facing each other. Each one simultaneously raises their halberd against the other, then swing. Cut to the player reacting to the moment of impact, heard off-screen.

Text.Value: Help me with my infernal engine, and I'll tell you.
I did my part - I filled these halls with ghosts. But Raphael's playing some other game - one that involves stiffing me.
We piss off a devil no matter what we do. Pick your poison - we'll handle the fallout like we always do.
Run.
My apologies. Try as I might, the surface-stink just won't wash off.
If you're wrong about this, I'll claw my way out of Avernus and eat you alive - contract be damned.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: <placeholder>

Text.Value: But you're too fresh for this place, aren't you? A dark-dweller you may be, but there's a definite whiff of the surface to you...
But you're too fresh for this place, aren't you? You may look like a dark-dweller, but there's a whiff of the surface to you...
But you're too fresh for this place, aren't you? There's a whiff of the surface to you...

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Orthon sniffs the air before delivering line.
EditorData.InternalNodeContext:
Tagged subnodes for:
- REALLY_UNDERDARK
- UNDERDARK/Not REALLY_UNDERDARK (ie disguised)
- Untagged
EditorData.NodeContext: Sniffs the air just before speaking, as if detecting something,
EditorData.SFXTags: [MO] [NoJira] - Sniffing sfx if not included in VO recording.

Text.Value: You trying to burrow back home, little rabbit?
Put that thing down. I'm here to talk.
Go on, tell the bastard. All the better for us if he keeps Raphael - busy.
I spent a century roaming these halls - I spilled every drop of Dark Justiciar blood that there was to spill. And you think you can do better?
Hah! There's my word. I agreed to a contract - one that hasn't yet been fulfilled.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sardonic. Short, bitter bark of a laugh at the start.

Text.Value: I don't serve Zariel. And I'm going up - not down.

Wander Shar's halls; hungry to slay;
Leave no Justiciar alive to obey.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The orthon sings to the player.

Text.Value: What's this? Fresh entertainment.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: <placeholder>

Text.Value: I'd never ally myself with such a fiend.
Holy shit. An orthon. Powerful devils - I wouldn't get on their bad side without a good reason.
I don't want to make it pretty - I want to silence it.
Show me this contract. Perhaps there's something you missed.
I would sniff you out in an instant. Prey like you always has a most distinctive scent, it's like...
If you won't speak, then you don't need to draw breath. Tell me what I want, or I'll feed you to my pet over a tenday, and keep you alive to watch.
...Kill Nessa?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The orthon looks at the displacer, who gazes back at him with an adoring purr.

Text.Value: Raphael wanted you to kill Dark Justiciars? Why?
You always hear the song, orthon. Kill yourself, be reborn in the Hells, break the contract.
Do nothing.
I'll have both, if I wish.

EditorData.NodeContext: Growled retort. 'Don't tell me what I want'

Text.Value: Something tells me you aren't going anywhere at all. You must know it too, reeking of fear as you do.
No trap is inescapable, trust me.
I still hear it!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Orthon drops his crossbow and produces a sword from behind his waist.
EditorData.SFXTags: [MO] [NoJira] - Foley - Drops crossbow and takes sword.

Text.Value: Ought you? The Dark Justiciars all failed - and made the most interesting noises as they died. Some even called out to other gods for help...
Oh, I intend to. The lyrics are clear - all who hear the song must die.
That silver tongue of yours is dangerous - bravo. I can't believe you actually pulled that off...

EditorData.NodeContext: Impressed. The player pulled off a very unlikely series of persuasion moments against a potential foe.

Text.Value: You've got the stench of the Hells about you - the stench of home. And a whiff of the surface besides.
*Both far away and all too close, you feel your patron's grin. A job well done.*
Don't insult me - I'd know if there was a justiciar down there.
But you're too fresh for this place, aren't you? You've got the stench of the Hells about you - the stench of home. And a whiff of the surface besides.
I'm not one to placate a devil, but the last thing we need is an orthon for an enemy. Fought one once, and my back has never been the same.
I caught the scent of that bloated carcass already - he's no more alive than the Dark Justiciars down here.
Pretty tune for a contract that says 'kill all Justiciars'.
I see the art of eloquence is alive and well. I'm awed, impressed, and a little bit scared of you right now.
My dear hunter, isn't it obvious? You must kill yourself - then you'll be free.
Diabolic deals in legend always have loopholes - we just need to find it.
What do you know of infernal machinery?

EditorData.NodeContext: To the orthon. Adversarial, but she's hoping he knows something useful.

Text.Value: Exactly. Kill yourself, complete the contract, and you'll be reborn in Avernus. Free.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Yurgir] turns the tip of the sword ariund and rams it into his own torso.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The orthon turns the tip of his sword around to face himself, and rams it into his own torso. He falls dead.

Text.Value: *Especially one with a built-in loophole. The song's last couplet is a clause that's near impossible to fulfil.*
I'm never going back to Avernus. But I'd be happy to send you there.
So he's responsible for the carnage down here. All those Dark Justiciars... slaughtered.

EditorData.NodeContext: Cool anger followed by a slight note of mournfulness as she realises she's facing the creature that killed many Shar followers

Text.Value: What are you doing? The devil told us to kill this thing, so let's stop chatting and kill it.
Raphael! I can smell him all over you. Where is he?!

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Explosive anger. Snarling, gesturing crossbow threateningly.

Text.Value: You are star-touched that is true, but...
Wait! You might have missed something, and I'm uniquely good at tracking things down.
Maybe you'll find a crossbow bolt down your throat easier to manage.

EditorData.NodeContext: Offended/aggressive at the player's insinuation he's unduly concerned about his contract.

Text.Value: Kill yourself, coward. Then you'll return to Avernus. You'll be free.
Raphael is a devil like all your kind - he deals in tricks. You probably missed a loophole in your contract.
Besides, I told you already - I'm bound to this place.
Pathetic. A dusk hag once claimed she dreamt of a future where I spared her, but even her weaselling is no match for yours. This ends now.
The lyrics are a trick. You've always had an audience - your followers. Get rid of them.
I've said too much already.
Exactly. Kill yourself, complete the contract, and you'll be reborn in Avernus. Free.
He killed Shar's faithful? Then he's due our congratulations before we butcher him.
I've got nothing to spit out - not for you, anyway.
Go on then - I'll enjoy watching you fail. But try to run, and you will regret it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Sardonic. Doesn't favour the player's chances. Tenday = in-universe period of time.

Text.Value: It's been some time since I had an audience. Any who hear it tend to die.
There's a necromancer called Balthazar elsewhere in the temple - perhaps he's the one you need to kill.
Careful -  I'm not sure we want Raphael as an enemy.
*You feel a chuckle of crackling fire in the back of your mind - it seems your patron enjoys a cleverly constructed contract.*
*There is an almost admiring thrum in the back of your mind. Your patron seems to enjoy a well-crafted contract.*
*A fey giggle sounds in the back of your mind - seems as though your patron enjoys a tricksy contract.*
That was incredible - I'm actually impressed! You have a wicked little mind.

EditorData.NodeContext: Emphasise each of the first three words. "That. Was. Incredible."

Text.Value: If I was burrowing, you'd never find me.
So this was the wardevil who slaughtered Shar's faithful. At Raphael's urging, no less.
Let's share our experiences about Raphael. Perhaps we can help each other.
*You feel your patron's prickling flame at the back of your mind - and its diabolic words on your tongue. It wants to help.*
I'll spare your life - that's ample reward.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Be happy with your lot, or else'

Text.Value: I may be trapped here, but I'm not without friends. If you break your word, they'll hunt you down and make your final moments a symphony of agony.
You wouldn't say that if you truly knew his mind. Just listen to the terms he gave me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Terse, foreboding. 'You've no idea what you're talking about'

Text.Value: I already have plenty of lackeys. All you have to offer me is your death.
Do I look like I'm offering charity? What will you give me in return?
I've had dealings with that devil. Maybe we can help each other.
Lies! My nose would recognise him anywhere.
No. He is not the answer. He is not my prey.
A new arrival, then. You burrowed too deep, little rabbit...
Raphael's a sly lyricist - he tricked you. Your followers heard your song and still live.
You - tiefling. You've got the stench of the Hells about you - the stench of home. And a whiff of the surface besides.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Yurgir] turns his aim from the player to the displacer beast, shoots it.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The orthon shoots the displacer with his crossbow.

Text.Value: A deception. The Dark Lady would approve of them trying to sway you.
I smell the depths below that is true, but...

Synopsis:
Dialogue with the Orthon, where he tells you it was ordered by Raphael to kill Ketheric's Dark Justiciars. The dialogue ends in combat, unless you succeed some very hard persuasions.
Orthon is huge, forboding and loves a good fight. He speaks in a low rumble and is TERRIFYING.
